name.text: ANDS SA Community Day
name.html: ANDS SA Community Day

description.text:
The ANDS SA Community Day is an opportunity for our South Australian Partners to come together and share knowledege about research data management and learn from the experiences of others with ANDS projects.
The day includes presentations and workshops from ANDS staff and current and completed ANDS projects. There will be several opportunities to network with people facing challenges similar to those you are facing.
When? 8:45am-4:00pm on Friday 29 June 2012
Where? Radford Auditorium, Art Gallery of South Australia, North Terrace, Adelaide
Directions
The event will begin before the Art Gallery itself is open. If you are coming from North Terrace, please walk down the Western (left hand) side of the Gallery to the round doors. A security guard will be there to let you in and direct you to the Radford Auditorium.
Program
Partners are welcome to attend the whole day or choose to attend selected sessions only.
Please share this invitation with colleagues who may be interested in attending.



8:45am

Arrival



9:00am

The Australian National Data Service
An opportunity to learn about ANDS activities and connections with other eResearch initiatives.
ANDS staff will be available to answer questions about ANDS' direction.



 

Morning Tea



10:30am

Project Achievements
Partners who have completed projects with ANDS will share project outcomes and respond to questions from newer ANDS projects.



11:30am

Making Connections
This session will provide an opportunity for attendees to move into break out groups to discuss questions and issues relevant to current projects.



 

Lunch



1:30pm

Project Progress
Partners with current ANDS projects are invited to share project progress and challenges to date.



2:30pm

Making Data Discoverable
This session will cover specifics of metadata best practice, including ANDS Activity and Party infrastructure projects.



 

Afternoon Tea
Open forum and questions

description.html:
The ANDS Qld Community Day is an opportunity for our Queensland Partners to come together and share knowledge about research data management and learn from the experiences of others with ANDS projects.

The day includes presentations and workshops from ANDS staff and current and completed ANDS projects. There will be opportunities to network with people facing challenges similar to those you are facing.

When? 9:00am-4:00pm on Wednesday 8 August 2012

Where? The Ship Inn, Cnr Stanley & Sidon Streets, Southbank Parklands, Brisbane

Directions and Parking

The event will be held in The Ship Inn function room which is upstairs. If you are driving, some short term on street metered parking is available. All day parking is available at a cost at the South Bank Parklands Undercover Car Park. See: http://www.visitsouthbank.com.au/parking

Program

Partners are welcome to attend the whole day or choose to attend selected sessions only.

Please share this invitation with colleagues who may be interested in attending.

8:45am

Arrival
9:00am

Welcome
9:15am

Project Achievements

Partners who have completed projects with ANDS will share project outcomes and respond to questions from newer ANDS projects.

Morning Tea
10:45am

New Project Group Presentations

Partners with current ANDS projects are invited to share project progress and challenges to date.
11:30am

Making Connections

This session will provide an opportunity for attendees to move into break out
Groups to discuss questions and issues relevant to current projects.
Lunch
1:00pm

The International Context

ANDS is very much engaged with the international data management community. Come along and hear an overview of recent activities.

1:30pm

National Collections

Come along to find out about the ANDS National Collections.
2:00pm

The Australian National Data Service

An opportunity to learn about future ANDS activities and connections with other eResearch initiatives.
ANDS staff will be available to answer questions about ANDS' direction.
2:45pm

ANDS Data Management Initiatives Forum

This forum will provide an update on current ANDS initiatives including DOIs, Data Interviews, RIF-CS training, ANDS Activity and Party infrastructure projects and provide an opportunity for you to ask questions.
4:00pm Close

<P><SPAN STYLE="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Calibri','sans-serif';">Data citation is recognised as one of the key practices underpinning the recognition of data as a primary research output rather than as a by-product of research. </SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN STYLE="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Calibri','sans-serif';"><STRONG>This Roundtable is aimed at those who wish to learn about, and contribute to, best practices for Data Citation for the Australian research community.</STRONG>  </SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN STYLE="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Calibri','sans-serif';">The roundtable format will have an emphasis on discussion and sharing. Those who come along will walk away with a strong understanding of the benefits as well as practical and technical facets of implementing data citation.</SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="font-size: medium; color: #003321;">When? </SPAN><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small;">9:00am-3.00pm on Thursday 9 August 2012</SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN CLASS="description"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"> Where? </SPAN>Level 7, Webb Centre (Bldg S02), Griffith University, South Bank Campus</SPAN><SPAN>, </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="street-address">226 Grey Street, South Bank</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="parcel">, </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="region">Brisbane (Behind the Ship Inn)</SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;">Program</SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">Partners are welcome to attend the whole day or choose to attend selected sessions only - please register for the whole day.</SPAN></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">Please share this invitation with colleagues who may be interested in attending.</SPAN><STRONG></STRONG></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">9.00    Why is Data Citation such a hot topic?</SPAN></STRONG><BR><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">What’s in it for institutions and researchers? Metrics for strategic planning. National and international perspectives</SPAN></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">10.30   Morning Tea</SPAN></STRONG><STRONG></STRONG></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">10.45   Technical considerations</SPAN></STRONG><BR><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">Minting DOIs using Cite My Data. When do I DOI? Making the most of optional DataCite metadata elements. Thomson Reuters Data Citation Index. Gold Standard Records and Cite-able records.</SPAN><BR></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">11.45   Policy implications</SPAN></STRONG><BR><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">Policies – examples. Workflows. Citation and data aggregators</SPAN></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">12.30 Lunch</SPAN></STRONG></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">1.00   Engaging with researchers and library staff (culture changing)</SPAN></STRONG><BR><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">Beginning the Data Citation journey. Winning hearts'n'minds with both sticks and carrot. Data Interviews</SPAN></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">2.00 The Australian Data Citation Roundtable community</SPAN></STRONG><BR><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">Promoting and populating Best practice examples.Keystones and lodestones but no millstones. Furthering the culture of Australian Data Citation Best Practice</SPAN></SPAN></P>
<P STYLE="text-align: left;"><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;"><STRONG><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small; color: #000000;">3.00 Close</SPAN></STRONG><BR></SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN STYLE="color: #003321; font-size: medium;">Directions and Parking<BR></SPAN></P>
<P><SPAN STYLE="font-size: small;">If you are driving, some short term on street metered parking is available. All day parking is available at a cost at the South Bank Parklands Undercover Car Park. description.text:
The QUT Gold Standard Record Exemplars Project was tasked with investigating issues of quality and richness with respect to research data description records considered for the Research Data Australia repository service.  This webinar will provide an overview of the project and the process involved in creating Gold Standard Records in RDA.

Who should come along? – Anyone involved in creating rich metadata records describing research data.

description.text:
What? This is the kick off meeting for The Citers Catchup - come along and help shape the future of data citation in Australia. As space is limited, book a meeting room and join as a group, to fit more of the Community in.  Add the virtual meeting link to your diary for this event
Who? Facilitators:  Gerry Ryder and Karen Visser (ANDS)
This Citers Catchup is for Librarians, Research Office staff, Data Managers - anyone at all with an interest in promoting or learning about how to maximise the benefits of acknowledging reuse of data. 
Why?Signing up to this first virtual Catchup doesn't commit you to anything - it is to see if the time is right to kick off this group and gauge what the Australian research community needs and wants in terms of finally getting their data products acknowledged and counted. If we decide to proceed, regular (monthly?) virtual catchups will be a chance to network, ask, learn, debate, share experiences and float ideas affecting data citation in your institution. 
 
ANDS will facilitate the group but it will belong to the community - low key and community focused, with input from everyone. 
 
This webinar will cover:

forming: who are we and why are we here?
storming: what are the burning issues we want to discuss?
norming: how will the community work? how often to meet is just right for us? how will we communicate between catchups? is there a priority for issues?
celebrating: deciding next steps

 
This meeting will not be recorded but brief notes of action items will be taken and circulated through registration emails.
 
More information....

description.text:
This is a workshop for those who want an update on what’s happening in the research data community and/or those who are coming into the research data/eResearch space. There will be plenty of time for discussion, questions, learning from peers, sharing perspectives and building an holistic understanding of who contributes to the “care and feeding” of one of Australia’s most valuable assets: our research data.
Who would benefit from coming along? These topics are of interest to Librarians, Researchers, Research Officers, Higher Degree Research/Early Career Researcher Support Staff, Data and Institution Repository Managers, State and Federal Government Staff Come along if you are:

working in areas which now, or will, include research data and their management
 are, or will be, engaged in a role which includes research data management 

You don’t need a background in research data management to attend, just an interest in learning about research data management and how you can contribute to managing Australia’s research data.
Who will be sharing their insights with us?
The workshop will be a mix of information packed and thought provoking short talks, followed by discussion to clarify and contextualise issues. Ideas will be illustrated using case studies, exemplars and when things didn’t quite go as the project plan envisaged.... Presenters will be from ANDS and local universities and research institutions and will be advised closer to the workshop.
 What will the workshop cover?
Part 1: Why research data management matters

Begin at the beginning: What is research data? What is research data management? What is open access?
Why should "we" care about caring for datasets and open data?
Who is working together to ensure Australia’s research data is a discoverable institutional and national asset: state and federal governments, institutions, librarians, researchers research officers, research support staff, data and institution repository managers
What's happening with research data management and eResearch in WA?
The role of the Australian Natioanal Data Service(ANDS) 
Australian funding agencies and research data management

Part 2: Adding value to research data
Explores elements of research data management which are critical to maximising the impact of research data and the profile of the researchers and institutions producing those data. This is a practical session looking at practices and resources you can use to support: ­­­

Discovery: metadata, vocabularies 
Connecting researchers and all research outputs
Reuse: licensing, sensitive data, access, IP­­­­
Reward: publication and citation

The day ends with a practical “where to from here” action plan.
Logistics:

morning tea, lunch and afternoon tea will be provided - please email karen.visser@ands.org.au with dietary requirements
more information: karen.visser@ands.org.au

description.text:
The Australian National Data Service (ANDS) invites you to an afternoon workshop exploring open research, open data and research impact.
 Featuring guest speakers Dr Heather Piwowar, Paula Callan, and Dr Virginia Barbour this workshop will:

Discuss the rise of “Generation Open” in defining a new norm for scholarship and research;
examine the concept of alternative metrics (altmetrics) and its application to research data;
detail tools that can track the impact of research datasets and discuss how these tools are empowering revolutions in open access publishing and open data repositories;
look in detail at how Impact Story is helping researchers to tell data-driven stories about their impacts; and
outline how researchers can be empowered to extend the influence and impact of their research.

Presenters will include:

Dr Heather Piwowar, Cofounder of ImpactStory
Dr Virginia Barbour, Medicine Editorial Director & Acting Biology Editorial Director, PLOS
Paula Callan, Scholarly Communications Librarian, Queensland University of Technology

Afternoon tea will be provided.

Who should attend?Participants will gain a deeper understanding of the concepts explored and develop an action plan to take home. Librarians, data managers, Research Officers, researchers, repository managers would find this afternoon of interest.


More information 

Contact: natasha.simons@ands.org.au

description.text:
ANDS invites you to attend seminars on tools and approaches to manage environmental data.  In these seminars, we'll hear from local and international experts about

the history and lessons learned from large ecological and environmental research programs, "big ecology"
the current impediments to data management and sharing
solutions and tools that overcome these challenges
new approaches to publishing and sharing data
future directions in how informatics can better enable science


Featured speakers include

Professor William (Bill) Michener is the Director of Data Observation Network for Earth (DataONE) - a National Science Foundation funded project that supports cyberinfrastructure development and community engagement for the biological, environmental, and Earth sciences to ensure the preservation, access, use and reuse of multinational science data


Dr Siddeswara Guru is Data Integration and Synthesis Coordinator at the Terrestrial Ecosystem Research Network - a Commonwealth-Queensland State jointly funded project to connect ecosystem scientists and enable them to collect, contribute, store, share and integrate data across disciplines


Dr David Turner has worked as a knowledge modeller with the Eco-informatics facility which is part of the Terrestrial Ecosystem Research Network, based at the University of Adelaide.  The work of the facility has focused on the challenges associated with storing, manipulating and providing access to diverse and complex data.  This has led to the creation of a number of novel solutions including the Australian Ecological Knowledge and Observation Service


Peter Doherty has been the Program Manager with the Atlas of Living Australia since 2009 and has a background in the design, delivery and management of large IT systems.


Hamish Holewa is the Project Manager of the Biodiversity and Climate Change Virtual Laboratory. Mr Holewa has lead a variety of national collaborative research eInfrastructure projects and has led the successful development of the Quadrant health participant management tool, AeRO Tick Maturity Model, the ANDS MODC Open River project and national user support framework for NeCTAR.  


This is a half day event, 9:00am - 2:00pm, with plenty of opportunity for questions, open discussions and networking.  Morning tea and light lunch will be provided.  Registration is free but places are limited.

Who Should Attend?
Anyone with an interest in tools that help improve data management and data sharing in environmental science is welcomed.   Whether you are a developer, system builder, data librarian, data manager, analyst or researcher, having the right tools is critical to your success.

contact: Paul Wong paul.wong@ands.org.au

description.text:
Venue: Dulcie Holyock Rm, Baillieu Library, University of Melbourne, ParkvilleHosted by: Australian National Data Service (ANDS) Cost: It is FREE to attend, however, places are limited and registration is requiredMorning tea will be provided 10.30-11am.
 
Research data from studies with human participants have not traditionally been published and shared to the same degree as other disciplines. This is often due to the potentially-sensitive nature of these data and concerns about navigating legal and ethical requirements. The great benefits of sharing these data are, however, becoming widely understood by funders and researchers as a means of reducing participant burden, expediting treatments, saving research costs, and gaining researcher recognition. With planning and understanding, human data can often be shared safely to great success! Come and discuss how.

This workshop will cover how human data can be shared safely, legally, and ethically. Including:

What sensitive data are, and when legal and ethical planning needs to occur
How researchers and data managers are already sharing health data, and their experiences and advice
When and how data needs to be confidentialised
Licensing data for re-use
Your own cases and experiences with expert input

Researchers who want to publish and share human data;
Research Support Staff with a role in the management of human data, research funding, or Human Research Ethics review

description.text:
When: Thursday, 21 May 2015 from 9:30 AM to 12:30 PM (AWST)

Where: Enterprise Room, Innovation Centre, 9 DeLaeter Way,  Bentley
Cost: Free to attend, however, places are limited and registration is required.

Research data is a valuable asset. Valuable to researchers, to research institutions and the broader research community. Did you know data assets can be licensed to manage their reuse and maximise attribution?   
 
Come along to this seminar if you, or your institution:

share research data with colleagues;
collaborate with state government depts or agencies;
publish data through data repositories;
make data publicly available to meet publisher, government or funder requirements.

 
Applying a licence to research data allows you to stipulate who can reuse your data and under what conditions. Applying an inappropriate licence, or no licence at all, means that others may not be able to use and cite your data, despite it being published.
 
Come along to this seminar and learn how to make the most of your research data assets.
--reap the benefits of licensing research data (get the attribution you deserve!)
--learn about the WA Whole of Government Open Data Policy and the opportunities it presents;
--hear about the licensing options available to you (AusGOAL, Creative Commons and more)
 

Hear from experts and have your questions answered. 


Special guest speaker: Baden Appleyard, National Programme Director, AusGOAL.
There will also be speakers from:

the university sector
WA state government and more




This seminar will be of interest to:


researchers who share or publish their research data
those with a role in copyright, IP management or data management.


  
This event is hosted by the Australian National Data Service (ANDS). It is FREE to attend, however, places are limited and registration is required. Morning tea will be provided.
 
As places are limited, if you register, and later find you are unable to attend, please let us know.

Learned how to improve the management of research data in your repository


Heard case studies from the repository community

Helped to create a resource for the repository community to help institutions better manage research data in their repositories.

description.text:
ANDS, NeCTAR, QCIF, Intersect, VICNode, eRSA and Pawsey have joined forces to organize a monthly Tech Talk virtual + face-to-face (V+F2F) meeting.  We will have a couple of inspiring online talks and a panel discussion on “Cloud Power Users”, followed by informal networking at the hub location.

We have three speakers confirmed:

Gerhard Weis (Griffith, BCCVL)
Rowland Mosbergen (Stemformatics)
Wojtek Goscinski (Project director of CVL, Monash eReseach Centre)


Who should come along?
The general purpose for this virtual + face-to-face meeting is twofold:

provide a national forum for developers working with research data and/or research data management to discuss topics of interest 
enable a dialogue between developers and NCRIS facilities (e.g. ANDS, NeCTAR and RDS)

This event is for anyone who wants to know more about tech aspects of data and NCRIS facilities:

developers
data scientists
researchers who are building data tools
data technologists
data librarians


How does V+F2F work?
Tell us which of the 5 hubs you'll be attending (on the next page when you complete this Eventbrite registration.)
Come along to one of the 5 hub locations to hear and see virtual (V) talks and panel discussions which will run for around an hour (3-4pm). You can ask questions and pose issues to the speakers and panel.

description.text:
Welcome to the Hobart 23 Things Gathering
Research data holds the key to many critical questions we face today. During 2016 the Australian National Data Service (ANDS) is facilitating the 23 (research data) Things self-directed learning program for anyone with an interest in research data management. Participants learn what research data is; Why it is such a global hot topic; How to find and re-use it, manage it, describe it, how to make it open to the world, and much more. 
This gathering is an opportunity for all Tasmanian participants and community discussion groups to get-together to share their learning in a convivial atmosphere, rich in people keen to manage, promote, use, share and discover the wealth of research data. 
All welcome. Morning tea provided.
Want to join the ANDS 23 Research Data Things?
It's never too late to start 23 Research Data Things! You can join in at any point and don't need to go back and complete previously released Things (unless you want to), and you can just do those Things that are of interest to you. Each Thing presents 3 levels of challenge and is released weekly in advance (see the poster).
There are many ways in which you can engage with others across Australia and beyond through webinar catch ups, online discussions on Meetup and local community groups near you, as well as this Tasmania-wide 23 Things Fling.
Want to talk to someone about this event?
Richard Ferrers, ANDS.  richard.ferrers@ands.org.au

name.text: Hobart: Sharing Health-y Data: Challenges and Solutions
name.html: Hobart: Sharing Health-y Data: Challenges and Solutions

description.text:
Date: Tues 28 June 2016, 2pm- 4pm Location:  Hobart City, Medical Science Precinct (MSP), Lecture Theatre 2 
Cohosted by: University of Tasmania & Australian National Data Service (ANDS)Cost: It is FREE to attend, however, places are limited and registration IS required
 
The benefits for researchers, institutions and the general public of sharing health and medical data are becoming more widely accepted and promoted. Sharing health data reduces participant burden, expediates treatment and responses to health events, saves research costs and recognises the efforts made to collect these valuable data. 
With planning and understanding, ‘healthy’ human data can often be safely shared with great success!
At the end of this workshop you will know:

what health and sensitive data are
what legal and ethical issues you need to consider before publishing and sharing health data
how to plan for data sharing in research ethics applications and consent forms
how data may be confidentialised
how to licence human data for re-use
what’s happening in local institutions.

You will hear from ANDS and local experts about their experiences and advice for publishing and sharing health data. The workshop will also enable valuable discussion with your peers.
This seminar will be of interest to:

researchers who are considering publishing and sharing human data from health and other disciplines
researchers who want to re-use health data
research support staff
data managers
research ethics committee members

This seminar is hosted by the Australian National Data Service (ANDS) and the University of Tasmania
 
Speakers include: 
Kate LeMay,  Pharmacist, Research data manager, and currently Senior Research Data Specialist, ANDS
Professor Alison Venn, Director, Menzies Institute for Medical Research (focusing on the Tasmanian Cancer Registry)
Brian Stokes, Manager of the Tasmanian Data Linkage Unit
 
Examples of published health datasets
 Open access:  Ford, J (2015)  De-identified dataset of the PALS (Pregnancy and Lifestyle Study), a community based study of lifestyle on fertitlity and reproductivt outcome. University of South Australia.
Mediated Access:  Mishra, G (2014) Australian Longitudinal Study on Women's Health. The University of Queensland Collection
 
Health data resources

ANDS Guide: Publishing Sensitive Data
ANDS webinar: Clinical data disclosure: the five Ps with Iain Hrynaszkiewicz, Nature Publishing  90 second summary  30 min full version

description.text:
Venue:  McDonald Room, RG Menzies Library, McDonald Pl, ANU
Coffee and tea from 9am, session starts at 9.30

The research data management landscape is rapidly evolving. The demand for research data has never been greater and the expectations in regards to their management are even higher. 
This seminar will provide an opportunity for ACT research data producers and consumers to come together to hear about:

recent initiatives, 
prospects for likely developments in the next years based on recent trends, and
future opportunities in research data.

Who should attend
This seminar is for those for whom research data, related current developments and trends is of interest from both the university and the government data sectors


researchers, principal investigators, research assistants
research managers, repository managers, data managers, data architects
librarians, research office, ethics committee members
and those with an interest in keeping up to date with the fast moving data landscape.



The program is yet to be finalised but will bring together perspectives from:


 data providers/aggregators/managers


Australian National Data Service: Dr Adrian Burton
data.gov.au: Mr Toby Bellwood
NCI: Dr Ben Evans

 those for whom the reuse, management and publication of research data is playing an increasingly important role eg  


Research Office: Dr Douglas Robertson (ANU), Dr Ksenia Sawczak (UC)

name.html: August Tech Talk: Imaging analysis tools

description.text:
ANDS, NeCTAR, QCIF, Intersect, VICNode, eRSA and Pawsey have joined forces to organize a monthly Tech Talk meeting. The general purpose for this meeting is twofold:

Provide a national forum for developers working with research data and/or research data management to discuss topics of interest 
Enable a dialogue between developers and NCRIS facilities (e.g. ANDS, NeCTAR and RDS)

Speakers:
We will have a couple of inspiring online talks and a panel discussion on “Imaging Analysis Tools”, followed by informal networking and refreshments at the hub location. Speakers for August Tech Talk:

Andrew Janke (University of Queensland)
Grischa Meyer and Lance Wilson (Monash University)
Mat Wyatt (AIMS)

Who should come along?
This event is for anyone who wants to know more about tech aspects of data and NCRIS facilities:

developers
data scientists
researchers who are building data tools
data technologists
librarians with an interest in the data tech aspects of librarianship

Perth: ARRC Boardroom (26 Dick Perry Ave, Kensington) (starts 1pm AWST)

description.text:
Step-by-Step though Things 13-23 Sprint to the Finish of 23 (research data) Things 
This step-by-step course is a guided session for those who like to hear the stories behind the data, work in a structured learning environment and want to chat with others about what you have learned. This course covers Things 13-23: including identifiers, data management plans, data literacy, publishers and funders, talking with others about data, geospatial data with a quick foray into some technical aspects of data management.
Step by step is for you if you:  

have done Getting started activities for at least Things 1-5 but the more Getting started Things 1-12 you have done, the more you will get out of this step-by-step course
feel you don't have an extensive background in data - this is a gentle introduction to the concepts in Things 13-23
want to work in pairs or on your own

want to finish your Things and celebrate with others!
There will be a quick break for tea/instant coffee and biscuits midway through this session

Here's the poster overview of 23 (rd) Things so you can see at a glance what's been included in the Things 13-23.
**Note: the Melbourne afternoon session covers the same 12-23 Things but is for those who want less structure and want to get on and complete their Things, but also have time for discussion.
Like to join us and the afternoon session 23 Things people for a light lunch and a celebration cake?  RSVP via the registration form.

Haven't heard of 23 (research data) Things?  
23 (rd) Things is a flexible, free, self directed, online course for people wanting to know more about how research data is managed, discovered and described.  Each Thing has 3 levels from Getting Started >  Learn More  > Challenge Me to suit any level from beginners, through to those wanting to really stretch their data capabilities. 
You will need to be familiar with some of the concepts covered in Things 1-12 to understand and enjoy this course.
Would it be for you?
23 (rd) Things assumes no prior knowledge but also caters for those who have already developed significant level of competence in research data support.  This short workshop would be valuable for people in roles where research data is, or will be, part of your workload i.e. do you want to find, use, describe, create, contribute to, and/or publish research data?

Research assistants, researchers
Librarians, Repository managers
Those working with Open Government Data initiatives
Those in research support and research impact roles
Those who feel that they need to know about research data for their current or future role 


What will happen in the workshop?
Networking and community building, hands-on data dabbling, discussion and exchange!  

You'll do a quick MyThings Audit where you work out which Things are most valuable to you and your current or future role.  
Then we'll data dabble and do a few Things at a time, interspersed with whole and small group discussions.
Finally, we'll meet others who have been doing 23 (rd) Things to chat about how they keep motivated and what they have got out of their Thing journey.


Who will run this 23(rd)Things Crash Course?
We'll have the ANDS people who have developed the course and data experts who will rove around to help you if you get stuck and also to talk with you about some of the trickier aspects of data dabbling. 

Don't hesitate to contact us for more information about this event

Richard.ferrers@ands.org.au
Karen.visser@ands.org.au
